# C. Analysis

---

## 🔹 Q1: Efficiency of Binary Search

Binary Search reduces the problem size exponentially:

* Each step halves the dataset
* Leads to O(log n) complexity

Thus, it performs efficiently even for large inputs.

---

## 🔹 Q2: Subset Sum Complexity

* Solving requires exploring all subsets → O(2ⁿ)
* Verification only needs summation → O(n)

Hence:

* Hard to solve
* Easy to verify

---

## 🔹 Q3: TSP Feasibility Limit

| Cities | Routes |
| ------ | ------ |
| 10     | 3.6M   |
| 12     | 479M   |
| 15     | 1.3T   |

Becomes infeasible at **10–12 cities** due to factorial growth.

---

## 🔹 Q4: Solving vs Verifying

| Aspect     | Solving     | Verifying  |
| ---------- | ----------- | ---------- |
| Time       | Exponential | Polynomial |
| Difficulty | Hard        | Easy       |

---

## 🔹 Q5: NP-Complete Problems

### Key Properties:

* Solutions can be verified quickly
* No known efficient solution exists

### Importance:

If one NP-complete problem is solved in polynomial time:
➡ All NP problems become solvable efficiently

---

# Conclusion

* Binary Search → Highly efficient (O(log n))
* Subset Sum → Exponential complexity (NP-Complete)
* TSP → Factorial complexity (NP-Hard).

This experiment highlights the difference between:

* Efficient algorithms
* Intractable computational problems

